                "style": "",
                "text": " that progressives in Michigan were trying to take over their state’s Democratic Party. The results of last Saturday’s election are in.According to Liano Sharon of the Michigan progressive group MI Solidarity, last week’s Saturday’s party elections were a rousing success. Sharon told ",
                "type": "text",
                "version": 1
              },
              {
                "detail": 0,
                "format": 0,
                "mode": "normal",
                "style": "",
                "text": "The Daily Poster",
                "type": "text",
                "version": 1
              },
              {
                "detail": 0,
                "format": 2,
                "mode": "normal",
                "style": "",
                "text": " that progressives can now rely on “between 50 and 90” votes on the state’s central committee, a huge increase from the 40 to -60 votes that progressives could count on before the election. “I won't know for sure until we start taking votes,” Sharon said. “I know we have allies who won on the Unity Slate, some of whom are new to the [state’s leadership committee]Committee. Could be as many as 90 on some issues, less on others.”",
